The Governments of the Netherlands nationalize part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - the first in Europe - will help with a nationalisation to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in trouble due to the impact of the mortgage crisis in the US market: the three countries will support a total of EUR 11.2 billion to this financial and insurance institution which also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the Governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's Head of Economic Competition.
Fortis Bank was the first to suffer from the crisis in the euro area in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so the decisions taken with regard to the Bank can in some ways be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken in the early morning of Sunday, the three States will purchase approximately half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will safely sell a part of its business, including all the activities - mainly insurance - purchased last year of the Dutch ABN Amró.
The actions of the Fortis began a strong decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with their 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company's actions only on Friday decreased by 12 percent, the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares decreased by more than two-thirds.
Noting the current prices of the shares, the total value of the group's capital on the market is about EUR 14 billion, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's leadership imposed the sudden fall of the actions of Fortis to the insecurity of the US market in relation to the approval of the US package plan of $700 billion.
On Monday, the actions showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new director general of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a specific offer.
The Belgian government had already ensured that investors had nothing to worry about, they are not going to lose their money.
Among the Bank's customers so far, no panic occurred, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased lease companies.
